In a world where most crypto projects have points programs, the core product will be what matters most. 

However, there are still best practices for points design. Outlining lessons from a recent discussion hosted by :
https://paragraph.xyz/@0x808a2adbd0a3fc679e3f7cd18d4f579bfcaaec9c/dissecting-the-points-meta

Points programs are the gamified manifestation of the first layer of Maslow's hierarchy of needs: physiological needs. They reward the customer with tangible benefits. 

True loyalty comes from upleveling users to higher tiers of Maslow's pyramid: self-actualization. The brand becomes intertwined with users' identity.

Points or tokens?

The two main characteristics that distinguish "points" from "tokens" are that the latter are (1) onchain and (2) freely transferable.

A major benefit of turning points into tokens is composability, which allows many different companies to honor points in a single ecosystem.

web3 vs web2 product development, in broad strikes:
- more community-driven (or can be)
- more building in public
- can be more accelerated due to composability
- less emphasis on user research because the market is new (imo)
- poorer understanding of product/growth best practices like onboarding, referrals, etc

I think the proliferation of AI content could actually lead to a centralization in terms of users' consumption - akin to a flight to quality in people's news/information diets in a world of UGC. That could mean social networks taking an active role in filtering for authenticity, and that being a basis of competition

An analogy could be that we like / consume a lot of things in the real world, but only sometimes collect / own them outright - think travel, rentals, etc.

Collect can definitely be a gamechanger for monetization, but I'm not sure it will change how we engage as much (more of a super-like)

In a world of user-owned social graphs, the value for app developers shifts to competing on the core product, instead of data lock-in

Think of podcasting or email applications: the differentiation is in the product experience (or user distribution in Apple's case), not the underlying data

- targeting crypto natives meant being able to bootstrap a large and compelling prize pool

Constructing the right graph that aligns onboarding w/ core product:

There's a tension in crypto social between bootstrapping initial interest and building an ongoing retentive social product, with founders often over-indexing on initial interest at the expense of retention. 1\

One common pitfall is building an onboarding mechanism that tries to bootstrap the wrong network (eg Threads piggybacking off Instagram's social graph). 

You have to align your bootstrapping mechanism with the *right* social graph and build a core product experience that is going to retain people in that graph
The question for builders going speculation-first is: what is your core product utility that's going to retain users?

Rather than directing tokens to re-create networks that already exist in web2, I think the focus should be on building net new marketplaces/networks that don't exist in web2, because the cost to bootstrap those networks is too immense. 

Tokens can help these "should exist" marketplaces exist

Examples:
- hyperlocal social networks (what's going on in a 1mi radius?)
- new innovations in dating apps (face immensely high CAC traditionally)
- licensed services marketplaces where the credentials could exist onchain, lowering the barrier to entry

There are two broadly paths that I’ve observed emerge for the future of consumer crypto:

2/ Crypto began in 2009 with one asset, Bitcoin, designed to be stateless money. Bitcoin is an example of a class of crypto products that treats crypto as the "why"–meaning crypto assets is the whole reason people want to use something. 

Crypto is extremely visible in these products...

3/ It’s the whole reason why people are there. This class of products that treat "crypto as the why" also includes memecoins, PFPs, and other products that put crypto at the center of their value proposition.

The target user for this class of products is typically early crypto adopters, degens, etc.

4/ But crypto isn’t just about money and assets – crypto is also a technology, and so in the past couple of years, we started seeing builders treating crypto as the "how." In these products, crypto is simply the technological tool that helps accomplish something.

5/ Crypto is invisible, and users are oblivious that there’s a blockchain at all.

This segment of products targets normal mainstream users who have a pain point and just want a product to solve that better.

6/ Both of those two categories of products are growing and I think will be immensely successful.

But what we’re seeing now, in addition, is a new wave of innovation that I call "Only with crypto": products that use the building blocks offered by crypto to create entirely new experiences.
7/ In this category, crypto unlocks entirely a new design space, and creates compelling experiences that simply weren’t possible before in web2.

8/ The segment of products that can be built "Only with crypto" have capabilities rooted in what crypto uniquely brings to the table:

- Global payment rails
- Composability of onchain assets and identity
- Creation of new markets and new assets

These elements combined unlock new experiences.

9/ Let's go through some examples!

Last month, I was a contestant in , a Survivor-esque online game show that took place over the span of 2 weeks.

There were a few dimensions of the game that were possible only with crypto.

10/ Firstly, it was built using crypto payment rails, enabling it to involve real money prizes and to be global from day 1 – the founder 
@DylanAbruscato said he couldn’t imagine building the game on any other financial rails.

11/ In the future, you could imagine the game introducing all sorts of novel mechanics leveraging crypto, like embedded prediction markets to allow audiences to bet on what happens next, adding in another layer of engagement beyond what’s possible in web2.

12/ Another example of "only with crypto" is new networks that couldn’t otherwise exist.

From my experience investing in marketplaces over the past 7+ years, I realized that there are a whole set of marketplaces & types of networks that should exist in the world but don’t, because of the immense cold start problem

13/ Examples range from new dating apps, to hyperlocal social networks, to marketplaces for various services – networks that plenty of web2 founders have tried to build, but have an immensely difficult time in getting off the ground or scaling.

14/ You could apply tokens as a new bootstrapping tool to build these networks. What excites me about this category is instead of directing tokens to re-create networks already exist in web2, you’re building net new networks that don't exist currently.

15/ Another example of something made possible only with crypto is new composable apps and distribution channels that connect to users' wallets to enable richer actions.

Last month saw the launch of  Frames, a framework for building mini-applications inside Farcaster.

16/ In other words, these applications meet users where they already spending time and where their wallet is already connected. Already we’re seeing developers use this new framework to create experiences from ordering Girl Scout cookies to minting NFTs from inside their social media feeds

17/ As an extension to that, composability allows you to create headless marketplaces that tap into global onchain liquidity, but the end user experience meets users wherever their wallets are connected. The end result is lower friction to transacting and deeper liquidity network effects.

18/ As an example, we’re already seeing prediction markets built as Farcaster frames - where users bet on certain outcomes from inside their social feed. cc 

(my partner 's post on headless marketplaces: https://jessewalden.com/go-where-the-wallets-are-headless-marketplaces/)

19/ Those are a few examples for products can be built “Only with crypto” – and there are new examples each day.

This is the category of applications and networks I’m most excited about, and what I believe will bring in next wave of users.

20/ Just like previous waves of tech companies in web1 and web2 were only possible on those new computing platforms, applications in web3 will take advantage of what crypto offers to provide experiences that can’t be found elsewhere.

As a long-time consumer investor, I’m very excited about this future!
